                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d148">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4 General Committee (Arms)/49:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chairman of the American Delegation</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Davis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-11-15T19:00:00+00:00"
                            >November 15, 1934—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 15—3:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>39. Your No. 16, November 9, 6 p.m. and No. 19, November 14, 5 p.m. In a talk
                    with Henderson today he agreed that the articles <pb facs="0281" n="181"
                        xml:id="pg_181"/> defining the organization of the Permanent Disarmament
                    Commission and the articles setting up the control of arms traffic and
                    manufacture should be embodied in the same protocol. He still feels, however,
                    that some provisions covering budgetary expenditure could be included in the
                    same protocol to be worked out at the present time. Repeated to Geneva.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Davis</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
